<m0>hen Robin Kaye Stilwell first began counseling families as a therapist 20 years ago, couples were trying to figure out how to communicate more with each other.<ep>
  ``We don't talk to each other anymore,'' the wife would complain.<ep>
  ``I don't understand her problem,'' the husband would reply.<ep>
  Communication is still a concern for the families of the late 1990s, but the people who walk into the offices of marriage and family therapists have changed. More and more, they reflect the transformations of society outside the clinic doors.<ep>
  ``We're seeing more same-sex couples, more blended families, more single parents,'' says Stilwell. ``Many of the problems have remained the same, but the people who are seeking help are more diverse.''<ep>
  As president-elect of the Florida Association for Marriage and Family Therapy, Stilwell will preside over the group's annual convention in Miami Beach next week. The three-day conference, beginning Thursday, seeks to mirror the changes members have witnessed in their practices. Among the sessions: Violence in Gay and Lesbian Couples, A School-Based Collaborative Systems Approach in a Haitian Community, Domestic Violence (--) Identification and Treatment.<ep>
  <m2><ql>
<ql>
